We remain one hundred percent focused on protecting public health and saving lives. We all have a role and need to continue to prioritize health and safety. I’m grateful for Arizona’s continued cooperation and partnership.  8/8

ENHANCED GUIDANCE:

We need businesses to continue to protect customers and employees. Enhanced guidance from @AZDHS will require physically distancing, face covers whenever possible, symptom checks for employees and increased cleaning and disinfecting. 7/

FOCUSED ON LONG-TERM CARE SETTINGS: 

With testing of all residents and staff recently completed, we’re providing an additional $10 million for more PPE and masks in long-term care settings. @AZDHS will continue to prioritize ongoing testing of residents and staff. 6/

ENHANCED EDUCATION CAMPAIGN:

We’re moving forward on the next iteration of a public awareness campaign, and expanding it. All Arizonans should continue to stay physically distant, stay home when sick and WEAR MASKS. #MaskUpAZ 5/

ENABLING LOCALIZED MITIGATION EFFORTS:

@AZDHS today released updated guidance allowing local governments to implement mask and face covering policies, allowing local authorities to tailor mitigation efforts specific to the local public health need. 4/

CONTACT TRACING:

I’m signing an Executive Order providing @AZDHS authority to implement a consistent, statewide system for contact tracing & making available 300 @AZNationalGuard to increase manpower. ADHS is also providing $37M to boost contact tracing locally & statewide. 3/

TESTING:

We're continuing to ramp up testing through a partnership with @ASU to scale up saliva-based testing. The less invasive test will allow for more rapid & accurate results while requiring less PPE & facilitating greater usage at workplaces & health care facilities. 2/

Protecting public health during this pandemic has been our highest priority, & it will continue to be. We know this is a marathon, not a sprint, & we need everyone to continue to follow the public health & safety guidance. I’m thankful to all Arizonans for their cooperation. 7/7

We’re continuing to focus on protecting those most vulnerable to the virus, including administering testing in our nursing homes and prison settings and ensuring proper infection control techniques continue to be utilized. 6/
And businesses need to continue to follow the public health guidance from @AZDHS and @CDCgov to keep employees and customers safe:  5/

Arizonans need to continue to do their part to slow the spread. That means physically distancing, washing your hands, using cloth face coverings when physical distancing is not an option, and staying home when sick. 4/

As our state gradually reopens & more people move about, we’re seeing increased transmission, which is to be expected. This is happening around the country. To be clear, however: our hospitals have capacity & anyone who might need health care due to #COVID19 has access to it. 3/

Today, we are prepared. We’ve grown the supply chain for PPE, stocked up on critical medical supplies like ventilators, built out more capacity at our hospitals and added additional surge beds on top of that, if needed, which today it is not. 2/

Over 90 days ago, Arizona declared a public health emergency related to #COVID19. Since then, we’ve worked aggressively to secure PPE, expand hospital capacity, ramp up testing, slow the spread of the virus and save lives. 1/

Been contacting mayors across Arizona today to ensure they have proactive plans to prevent looting and violence in their cities tonight and in days to come. This is why we sought public office. It’s time for leadership, vigilance and action.

@Arizona_DPS @PhoenixPolice @AZNationalGuard This kind of leadership from law enforcement, working with community leaders, will get us through. But we cannot, and will not stand for violence, looting, and criminal activity. 8/8

@Arizona_DPS @PhoenixPolice @AZNationalGuard In Arizona, we will listen ⁠— and this was demonstrated by the leadership DPS Colonel Heston Silbert displayed on Thursday night as he engaged with protestors at the Capitol. 7/

@Arizona_DPS @PhoenixPolice @AZNationalGuard The death of George Floyd is tragic and abhorrent. It should be condemned by leaders at all levels ⁠— and we should listen to those who seek to have a civil dialogue on how to ensure it never happens again. 6/

@Arizona_DPS @PhoenixPolice @AZNationalGuard What we are seeing is happening in cities and states everywhere in America, and Arizona leaders need to be on high alert. They need a plan. Today should be a working day for every local elected leader, city manager, police chief and sheriff in every jurisdiction in the state. 5/

@Arizona_DPS @PhoenixPolice @AZNationalGuard I'll be speaking w/ mayors around the state to ensure plans are in place to prevent this kind of lawlessness tonight & beyond. The state will provide all resources we can, through DPS, Nat. Guard, & coordination of local law enforcement. Every community needs to be prepared. 4/

@Arizona_DPS @PhoenixPolice @AZNationalGuard The looting and violence we saw last night, especially in Scottsdale, simply cannot be tolerated. And it won't be. Destruction of property does not qualify as freedom of expression. 3/

@Arizona_DPS @PhoenixPolice @AZNationalGuard One thing is clear: The more aggressive approach downtown was needed, and it worked. Now, more needs to be done, in more places around the state, to protect law and order and public safety.  2/

.@ArizonaDES continues to get needed assistance to those out of a job or hurting financially because of #COVID19. Since April, nearly $1.5 billion has been provided to serve more than 700,000 Arizonans impacted, with more to come. 9/
Lastly, we’re announcing public health guidance for organized youth sports and activities to resume. That full guidance can be found here:  8/

Next, we’re planning ahead to get kids and teachers safely back in the classroom for the start of the fall school year. We’ve worked closely with @Supt_Hoffman, school leaders, teachers, parents and public health experts. More details will be announced next week. 7/

Second, we’re announcing a responsible plan developed by @AZDHS that protects the health of kids in school-based child care, while allowing for increased child care capacity. This plan is a direct result of our meeting with school superintendents this week. 6/

We’re working closely w/ leaders in health care, business, education & more. Today we’re taking additional action based on their feedback. The first is a new order increasing collaboration among our hospitals & ensuring patient transfers can take place smoothly & efficiently. 5/

Yesterday, we announced nearly $600 million that’s going to support local governments and nonprofit entities on the frontlines of #COVID19. These dollars are designed with flexibility and speed in mind — so more resources can get where they’re needed faster. 4/

We also continue to expand testing throughout our prisons, including making available antibody tests for all correctional officers. And @AZNationalGuard continues to coordinate with tribal leaders throughout AZ to supply the necessary PPE, medical supplies, food, water & more. 3/

With the #AZTestingBlitz in place, testing continues to be a priority. @AZDHS continues to test all residents and staff in our nursing homes and long-term care facilities. We know they are our most vulnerable and they are our top priority. 2/

Arizona continues to move forward with a calm and steady approach. This includes closely tracking the data, following the guidance of public health officials, and continuing to put health and safety first. 1/

Gating criteria 4: Testing ✅
 
Arizona has expanded both diagnostic and antibody testing, and has accelerated plans to test all residents and staff of long-term care facilities, as well as those within our prisons. 5/

Gating criteria 3: Hospitals ✅
 
With new hospital beds and surge capacity ready, Arizona continues to have more than ample hospital capacity and treat all patients without crisis care. 4/

Gating criteria 2: Cases ✅
 
As testing has rapidly expanded, Arizona is experiencing a four-week downward trajectory of positive cases as a percentage of total diagnostic tests. 3/

Gating criteria 1: Symptoms ✅
 
Arizona has experienced a five-week downward trajectory of COVID and Influenza-like symptoms reported at our hospitals. 2/

What to expect next: 

We will continue to put public health first. 

We will continue to take a step-by-step approach to reenergizing our economy guided by facts & health officials. 

And we will continue to prioritize giving businesses and citizens time to plan and adjust. 6/6

When it comes to dine-in… we’re aspirational. Our goal is to open in May. We aren’t there today, but we want to start preparing. We’re looking at the data and we’re listening to the industry. More guidance to come. 5/

Last week, we announced the ability for hospitals and outpatient surgical centers to resume elective surgeries. 

Much like today’s announcement, our approach is to resume gradually, with assurances that these facilities have adequate supplies and PPE.  4/

We’re also continuing to breathe life back into our economy. We’ve seen our big box stores innovate; let's allow other retail to do the same. Starting next week, retail stores can begin to partially re-open with sanitation and physical distancing measures in place. 3/

Physical distancing is working. We’re slowing the spread. We’ve made significant progress & can’t let up. That’s why I'm extending AZ's Stay Home, Stay Healthy, Stay Connected Order until May 15. This is the right thing to do based on the data & information we have right now. 2/

Had a productive call with @RepAndyBiggsAZ to discuss ways to support rural hospitals and the needs of Arizonans around the state, including our small business owners. I’m grateful for his partnership as we work to slow the spread of #COVID19 and get relief to Arizonans.

One thing is for sure: Arizona has been through tough budget situations before, and we’re smarter and wiser. We've got a great team in place across state government, and we’ll be calling upon all our experience and expertise to make the best decisions possible.  7/7

There will be tough decisions to make about our budget, and we’re prepared to make them. Our priorities will be the priorities we've had throughout my administration — public health & safety and education. 6/

We also must continue to take all steps to get assistance to Arizonans struggling now because of this virus. To this end, the federal government has made relief available — and Arizona will be taking full advantage to support our families, individuals and businesses. 5/

Right now, our focus must remain on the public health emergency before us — ensuring our hospitals are prepared, securing enough PPE and supplies for our health care professionals and slowing the spread of #COVID19. 4/
The good news — Arizona was fiscally responsible when times were good. Our Rainy Day Fund has $1 billion, and we’ve made prudent decisions about spending. We haven't overspent or overcommitted. 3/

Businesses are closed, and tax collections have plummeted. There's a tremendous amount of uncertainty in our economy. It's why in my budget signing letter on March 28, I wrote about how our job isn’t done and that there are many tough decisions ahead of us. 2/

My budget office has been closely analyzing the impact of #COVID19 on our state's finances since this public health crisis began. We've been working closely with the legislature, and their forecasts track closely with ours. 1/
